I just want to print out a message, I am using this codes:

```
string resultStr;
detectionResult.SerializeToString(&resultStr);
printf("%s", resultStr.c_str());
```
`detectionResult` is my message. But it just got some unicode binary outputs rather than strings and numbers, just not as prototxt beautiful json-like string was.

I also try to save my Message into a prototxt file which I believe more readable then binary.
```
char* saveTxtFile = "det.prototxt";
    int f = open(saveTxtFile, O_WRONLY|O_CREAT|O_TRUNC);
    auto outputTxtFile = new FileOutputStream(f);
    if (!google::protobuf::TextFormat::Print(detectionResult, outputTxtFile)) {
        cao::Log(kError, "error in save to prototxt");
    }
```

This gives me an error, I remove the file and try again, it saved blank message. What is the right way to do this? Forgive my ignorance on protobuf but it's really leak of examples on this.

define enum type in some.pbobjc.h:
typedef GPB_ENUM(someStatus) {
  Status_GPBUnrecognizedEnumeratorValue = kGPBUnrecognizedEnumeratorValue,
  StatusNotStart = 0,
  StatusStart = 1,
  StatusPaused = 3,
  StatusStop = 4,
};
define a Property in otherClass like this:
@property (nonatomic, assign) someStatus type;

otherClass.type = StatusNotStart;//can not be seted the zero-value
otherClass.type = StatusStart;//if the value is not zero-value it can be seted correctly

When calling `serializeToJsonString `, the Message object in the C Extension does not escape slashes, causing an error in the following code:

```php
   // add this to tests/encode_decode_test.php
    public function testJsonEncodeEscaping()
    {
        $string = 'this\\/should/be/escaped';
        $from = new TestMessage();
        $from->setOptionalString($string);
        $data = $from->serializeToJsonString();
        $to = new TestMessage();
        $to->mergeFromJsonString($data);
        $this->assertEquals(
            $from->getOptionalString(),
            $to->getOptionalString()
        );
    }
```

Another less important but still pressing issue can be seen in [this test](https://travis-ci.org/googleapis/gax-php/jobs/326584734#L2834), which shows that the native library escapes slashes but the C extension does not:

```php
   // add this to tests/encode_decode_test.php
    public function testJsonEncodeEscapeForwardSlash()
    {
        $string = 'this\\/should/be/escaped';
        $from = new TestMessage();
        $from->setOptionalString($string);
        $data = $from->serializeToJsonString();
        $this->assertContains(json_encode($string), $data);
    }
```

**Note**: Both of these tests pass when the `google/protobuf` composer package is used instead.

pull_requests.body:
Generate php file for the **plugin.proto**, so that we can use php to develop protoc-gen-plugin.

Also fix the issue #3220

And here is a demo,

```php
<?php
require './vendor/autoload.php';

$input = file_get_contents("php://stdin");
$request = new Google\Protobuf\Internal\CodeGeneratorRequest;
$response = new Google\Protobuf\Internal\CodeGeneratorResponse;
$request->mergeFromString($input);

/** @var \Google\Protobuf\Internal\FileDescriptorProto $fs */
$fs = $request->getProtoFile()[0];
$package = $fs->getPackage();

$f = new \Google\Protobuf\Internal\CodeGeneratorResponse_File();
$f->setName("foo.php");
$f->setContent("<?php // $package\n");

$response->setFile([$f]);

file_put_contents("php://stdout", $response->serializeToString());
```

